# {{lb|en|dated|now|offensive}} Black or dark brown in color.

====Usage notes====
In the United States of America, the word {{m|en||negro}} is considered acceptable only in a historical context or in proper names such as the {{w|United Negro College Fund}}. {{m|en|black|Black}}, which replaced ''negro'' from 1966 onward, or the more recent {{m|en|African-American}} (from the 1980s), are the preferred alternatives, with neither being categorically preferred as an [[endonym]] (self-designation) or by publications.

Before 1966, {{m|en||negro}} was accepted and in fact the usual endonym – consider ''{{w|The Negro}},'' 1915, by {{w|W. E. B. Du Bois}} – which itself replaced the older {{m|en|colored}} in the 1920s, particularly under the advocacy of Du Bois (who advocated capitalization as {{m|en|Negro}}). Following the coinage and rise of {{w|Black Power}} and {{w|Black pride}} in the 1960s, particularly after 1966, the term {{m|en|black}} (occasionally {{m|en|Black}}) became preferred, and {{m|en||negro}} became offensive; in 1968 {{m|en||negro}} was still preferred by most as a self-designation, while by 1974 {{m|en||black}} was preferred; usage by publications followed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2241120/ |title=When Did the Word Negro Become Taboo? |work=Slate |last=Palmer |first=Brian |date=2010-01-11 |website=Slate |series= |publisher=The Slate Group |location=Washington, DC |quote=The turning point came when Stokely Carmichael coined the phrase ''black power'' at a 1966 rally in Mississippi.}}</ref>

See also [[w:African American#Terms no longer in common use|discussion at Wikipedia]].

